<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is a PEM-encoded certificate?", answer: "PEM (Privacy-Enhanced Mail) is the most common format for SSL/TLS certificates. A PEM certificate is Base64-encoded and wrapped between -----BEGIN CERTIFICATE----- and -----END CERTIFICATE----- markers. The encoded data contains the certificate in ASN.1 DER binary format. PEM files typically have .pem, .crt, or .cer extensions. You can view PEM certificates in any text editor." },
  { question: "What are Subject Alternative Names (SANs)?", answer: "Subject Alternative Names are a certificate extension that lists additional domain names and IP addresses the certificate is valid for. Modern browsers require SANs and ignore the Common Name (CN) for domain validation. A single certificate can cover multiple domains (e.g., example.com, www.example.com, api.example.com) through SANs, which is how wildcard and multi-domain certificates work." },
  { question: "What does a self-signed certificate mean?", answer: "A self-signed certificate is one where the issuer and subject are the same entity, meaning the certificate was signed by its own private key rather than by a trusted Certificate Authority (CA). Self-signed certificates are not trusted by browsers by default and will trigger security warnings. They are commonly used for development, testing, and internal services where public trust is not required." },
  { question: "Why do SSL certificates expire?", answer: "Certificates expire to limit the damage from compromised private keys, ensure organizations regularly verify their identity, allow adoption of stronger cryptographic algorithms, and maintain an accurate certificate ecosystem. Maximum certificate lifetimes have been reduced over the years. As of 2024, publicly trusted certificates can have a maximum validity of 398 days (approximately 13 months). Shorter lifetimes reduce the window of vulnerability." },
  { question: "What is the difference between DV, OV, and EV certificates?", answer: "Domain Validation (DV) certificates only verify domain ownership and are issued within minutes. Organization Validation (OV) certificates additionally verify the organization's legal identity. Extended Validation (EV) certificates require the most thorough vetting, including legal, physical, and operational checks. All three provide the same level of encryption. The difference is in the identity assurance. DV is most common due to free issuers like Let's Encrypt." }
]) %>

